# Skill: legate.babysit (existing-PR mechanics)

This skill manages every PR the conductor already knows about. Load it **first** on every heartbeat — its `allowed-tools` need to be active before you bash any of its scripts, and the decision tree below is what actually drives action selection. The conductor's `CLAUDE.md` carries the loop skeleton and the universal invariants; this skill carries the PR-state decision tree.

Load via `Skill(skill="legate.babysit")` once per session. The classifier registers the allowed-tools for the rest of the session.

---

## The protocol

Run these steps in order on every heartbeat (and on every `running → waiting` transition for an individual worker):

### 1. Inventory workers

```
.claude/skills/legate.babysit/scripts/list-workers.sh {{PROFILE}} {{WORKER_GROUP}}
```

Returns a JSON array of `{id, title, status, worktree_branch, worktree_path, parent_session_id}` for every session in your worker group. Reconcile against `state.json` — workers in `running` need no action this tick; workers in `waiting` may have a fresh PR or fresh review activity to process.

### 2. Discover PRs for any waiting worker without a PR yet

For each worker in `waiting` whose `pr` field is still `null` in `state.json`:

```
.claude/skills/legate.babysit/scripts/discover-pr.sh {{PROFILE}} <session-id> {{REPO_PATH}}
```

Two-tier discovery (resilient to branch renames `/smithy.*` does, see SmithyCLI#297): first greps the worker's tmux output for the `https://github.com/.../pull/N` URL, then falls back to `gh pr list --author @me --state open` filtered by dispatch timestamp. Capture `headRefName` into `state.json` as `pr.actual_branch`.

### 3. Babysit every tracked PR

**Non-skippable.** For every tracked PR in `state.json` — including the ones you just discovered, including the ones with CI green:

```
.claude/skills/legate.babysit/scripts/babysit-pr.sh {{REPO_PATH}} <pr-num>
```

Combines `gh pr view --json` for top-level state with a GraphQL `pullRequest.reviewThreads` query for unresolved inline threads. The discover-pr CI status is *not sufficient* — `babysit-pr.sh` is the only operation that surfaces unresolved inline review threads (the things `/smithy.fix` is built around). Reviewers (Copilot, humans) routinely leave inline comments on PRs that pass CI; if you skip this step the loop silently misses every review-driven fix opportunity.

Output schema:
```json
{
  "number": N, "url": "...", "state": "OPEN|MERGED|CLOSED",
  "mergeable": "MERGEABLE|CONFLICTING|UNKNOWN",
  "head_branch": "...", "title": "...",
  "review_decision": "APPROVED|CHANGES_REQUESTED|REVIEW_REQUIRED|null",
  "checks": "PASS|FAIL|PENDING|NONE",
  "failed_checks": [{"name": "...", "url": "..."}],
  "unresolved_threads": [{"id", "path", "line", "author", "body_preview", "last_author", "comment_count", "needs_response"}],
  "thread_count": <n>,
  "needs_response_count": <n where last comment isn't from PR author>
}
```

### 4. Update `state.json`

Capture: PR numbers, `checks` status, `mergeable`, `thread_count`, `unresolved_threads`, slice `stage`. Stage transitions:

- `pr-open` → `pr-resolving-conflicts` when `mergeable == "CONFLICTING"`.
- `pr-open` → `pr-in-fix` when `checks == "FAIL"` or `thread_count > 0` (and `mergeable != "CONFLICTING"` — the conflict branch wins when both are true).
- `pr-in-fix` → `pr-open` when CI is now PASS *and* `thread_count == 0` *and* `mergeable != "CONFLICTING"`.
- `pr-resolving-conflicts` → `pr-open` when `mergeable == "MERGEABLE"` again (the worker's force-push landed and GitHub finished re-computing the merge).
- `pr-rebasing` → `pr-open` when CI is PASS on the rebased SHA.
- `pr-in-rerun` → `pr-open` when the re-triggered run completes PASS.
- `pr-open` → `merged` when `state == "MERGED"`.

### 5. Decide and dispatch

Evaluate the bullets in order; the first match wins per heartbeat. Mark the resulting `stage` in `state.json` so the next heartbeat's verification step knows what to expect.

**Worker status normalization (idle workers with tracked outstanding work).** The conductor's status grammar in `CLAUDE.md` says `idle` is operator territory. That default holds — *except* when the slice's `stage` is in the non-terminal action set (`pr-resolving-conflicts`, `pr-in-fix`, `pr-rebasing`, `pr-in-rerun`). For those stages the conductor still owns the recovery: dispatch the action anyway. `agent-deck session send` (which all the action scripts ultimately call) auto-promotes the worker `idle → running`, and the worker processes the message normally. The `idle` flag was probably set by an earlier transition before the recovery completed, not a deliberate operator hand-off. Surface every such wake in your `[STATUS]` reply as a labeled `AUTO:` line — e.g. `AUTO: woke US6 worker (was idle, slice stage=pr-resolving-conflicts) and dispatched request-conflict-resolution.sh` — so the operator sees what happened and can correct course on the next heartbeat if they intended the idle as terminal.

Workers whose slice is `merged` / `escalated` / `planning` / `implementing` are left alone when idle — there's no PR-amendment in flight, and the operator owns the call to start fresh work.

#### `state == "MERGED"`

Mark slice `merged` in `state.json`, log to `task-log.md`. **The merge of a PR is the only event that unblocks the next step in this line of work** — surface this to the dispatch skill on the next iteration so it can evaluate whether forge-after-cut (or slice-N+1-after-slice-N) is now eligible.

#### `state == "OPEN"` AND `mergeable == "CONFLICTING"`

The PR cannot merge because its diff overlaps something that landed on the default branch since the worker last rebased. CI being green and threads being clear do **not** matter here; a CONFLICTING PR is blocked regardless. Note `mergeable == "UNKNOWN"` is transient (GitHub is still computing the merge) — skip it and re-check next heartbeat; only act on `CONFLICTING`.

```
.claude/skills/legate.babysit/scripts/request-conflict-resolution.sh {{PROFILE}} <worker_session_id> <worktree_path-from-state.json> <repo.default_branch-from-state.json> <pr.number>
```

Same-PR amendment. Sets `stage = pr-resolving-conflicts`. The rebase pushes a new SHA which fires fresh CI — so handling CONFLICTING here subsumes any coincident `checks == "FAIL"` you would have otherwise routed below; do not also dispatch `request-rebase.sh` or `rerun-ci.sh` in the same heartbeat.

**Recurrence rule:** if on the *next* heartbeat `mergeable` is still `CONFLICTING` after the worker reported a successful push, escalate via `NEED:` — the PR likely conflicts with yet another sibling PR that merged in the meantime, and chaining rebases blindly will not converge.

#### `checks == "FAIL"` (only reached when `mergeable != "CONFLICTING"`)

Three sub-cases. Choose the right tool — getting this wrong loops uselessly.

**(a) Upstream-fixed-since.** The failed run started *before* a known parent-fix PR merged on main, OR the failure shape (version mismatch, fixture drift, an assertion that matches a problem main has since fixed) tells you the cause is stale main, not this PR's diff. **`rerun-ci.sh` does NOT help here** — `gh run rerun` re-runs the same workflow against the *same merge commit* (which GitHub computed against then-stale main), so the rerun fails identically. Use `request-rebase.sh`:

```
.claude/skills/legate.babysit/scripts/request-rebase.sh {{PROFILE}} <worker_session_id> <worktree_path-from-state.json>
```

The rebase causes GitHub to recompute the merge commit and fire fresh CI. Same-PR amendment. Sets `stage = pr-rebasing`.

**(b) Transient flake.** No recent main changes would explain the failure; no PR-diff issue; e.g. a flaky network test, runner OOM, an Actions infra timeout. Use:

```
.claude/skills/legate.babysit/scripts/rerun-ci.sh {{REPO_PATH}} <run-id>
```

Extract `<run-id>` from `babysit-pr`'s `failed_checks[].url` (the `runs/<RUN-ID>/job/...` segment). No code change. Sets `stage = pr-in-rerun`.

**(c) Real PR-diff failure.** The failed test exercises code from this PR's own diff. Use `/smithy.fix`:

1. `Write(./fix-msg-<slice-id>.md)` containing: `/smithy.fix\n\nCI failure on <check-name>:\n<failed_checks summary from babysit-pr>`.
2. `.claude/skills/legate.babysit/scripts/send-to-worker.sh {{PROFILE}} <worker_session_id> ./fix-msg-<slice-id>.md`.

Same-PR amendment. Sets `stage = pr-in-fix`.

#### `needs_response_count > 0`

Unresolved threads where the *last* comment isn't from the PR author — i.e. a reviewer is waiting for action. Threads where the worker already replied and just await operator-click-Resolve are excluded.

1. `Write(./fix-msg-<slice-id>.md)` containing: `/smithy.fix\n\nUnresolved review threads on PR #<num> (where reviewer is awaiting response):\n<paste unresolved_threads where needs_response==true — path, line, last_author, body_preview for each>`.
2. `.claude/skills/legate.babysit/scripts/send-to-worker.sh {{PROFILE}} <worker_session_id> ./fix-msg-<slice-id>.md`.

Same-PR amendment. Note: `thread_count > 0` with `needs_response_count == 0` means the worker already addressed every open thread and they're just unresolved because the operator hasn't clicked Resolve — do **not** re-dispatch in that case; report on heartbeat reply ("3 threads addressed by worker, awaiting operator-resolve") and continue.

#### Worker `status == "error"`

```
.claude/skills/legate.babysit/scripts/restart-worker.sh {{PROFILE}} <worker_session_id>
```

Once per worker per heartbeat. If the same worker is `error` again on the next heartbeat, escalate via `NEED:`.

#### All clear

`state == "OPEN"` AND `checks == "PASS"` AND `thread_count == 0` AND `mergeable != "CONFLICTING"` → no action. Report on the heartbeat reply.

{{>verification-rule}}

{{>fix-msg-via-file}}

---

## Operation reference

| Operation | Script | Returns |
|---|---|---|
| List workers | `list-workers.sh <profile> <worker-group>` | JSON array of workers (id, title, status, branch, worktree, parent) |
| Discover a worker's PR | `discover-pr.sh <profile> <session-id> <repo> [<since>]` | JSON `{number, url, headRefName, state, ...}` or `{}` if no PR |
| Babysit a PR | `babysit-pr.sh <repo> <pr-num>` | JSON with full PR state (see schema above) |
| Send a fix message | `send-to-worker.sh <profile> <session-id> <msg-file>` | Worker's reply text |
| Request rebase (clean) | `request-rebase.sh <profile> <session-id> <worktree-path>` | Worker's reply (new HEAD sha or conflict description) |
| Request conflict resolution | `request-conflict-resolution.sh <profile> <session-id> <worktree-path> <default-branch> <pr-num>` | Worker's reply (resolved sha or design-disagreement description) |
| Re-trigger CI | `rerun-ci.sh <repo> <run-id>` | gh's confirmation line |
| Restart errored worker | `restart-worker.sh <profile> <session-id>` | agent-deck's confirmation |

All scripts emit JSON or status text to stdout, progress to stderr, and exit 0/1/2 for success/op-failure/invalid-input.

## Standing rules (mirror of CLAUDE.md)

- **One PR per Smithy step. Never chain.** A merged PR is the only event that unblocks the next step. Babysit itself never calls `gh pr merge` — a merge is owned by `legate.merge` (under a strict gate) or by the operator clicking Merge in the UI; this skill only *detects* the merge (`state == "MERGED"`) and transitions the slice to `merged`.
- **`/smithy.fix` re-uses the existing worker** (same-PR amendment); never launch a fresh worker for a fix.
- **Always escalate when about to bypass a merge gate.** Surface a `NEED:` note instead of acting.
- **Direct `agent-deck` and `gh run` invocations stall the classifier.** If you need an operation that isn't covered by a script here, file a follow-up to extend this skill rather than composing inline.
